    {
        "content": "<p><span aria-label=\"search\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f50d\" role=\"img\" title=\"search\">:search:</span> <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Init/Prelude.html#Nat.succ\">Nat.succ</a>, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Init/Prelude.html#Nat.le_succ\">Nat.le_succ</a>, and <a href=\"https://loogle.lean-lang.org/?q=%22succ%22\">2976 more</a></p>",
        "id": 537133158,
        "sender_full_name": "loogle",
        "timestamp": 1756740755
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No idea where they all come from...</p>",
        "id": 537133218,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Stoll",
        "timestamp": 1756740773
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In any case, I agree that doing it \"correctly\" is the way to go: as more get corrected, the proportion will get more and more skewed to being wrong.</p>",
        "id": 537133352,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1756740815
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The linter could flag all constants that have \"succ\" in the name, but don't have \"succ\" in any constant name in the type.</p>",
